COLORCODES ANSI COLOURCODES COLOR-CODES COLOUR-CODES COLOR-LEVEL COLORS COLOURS PCOLORS COLORCODING
@n 
@nThe special character used to indicate the start of a colour sequence is 
@n'@*' (i.e. a SINGLE at-sign).  When you start a color code you must
@nterminate the color with the color code 'n' to stop bleeding.
@n
@n The predefined colours are:
@n
@n   n: no colour (switches colour off)
@n 
@n   @rr: dark red@n                        @RR: light red@n
@n   @gg: dark green@n                      @GG: light green@n
@n   @bb: dark blue@n                       @BB: light blue@n
@n   @yy: dark yellow@n                     @YY: light yellow@n
@n   @mm: dark magenta@n                    @MM: light magenta@n
@n   @cc: dark cyan@n                       @CC: light cyan@n
@n   @ww: dark white@n                      @WW: light white@n
@n 
@n   @aa: dark azure@n                      @AA: light azure@n
@n   @jj: dark jade@n                       @JJ: light jade@n
@n   @ll: dark lime@n                       @LL: light lime@n
@n   @oo: dark orange@n                     @OO: bright orange@n
@n   @pp: dark pink@n                       @PP: light pink@n
@n   @tt: dark tan@n                        @TT: light tan@n
@n   @vv: dark violet@n                     @VV: light violet@n
@n   @dd: dark grey/black@n                 @DD: light grey@n
@n   @__: underlined (if supported)@n       @++: bold (if supported)@n
@n   @--: blinking (if supported)@n         @==: reverse (if supported)@n
@n   *: at-sign@n
@n 
@n   @11: base palette 1@n                  @22: base palette 2@n
@n   @13: base palette 3@n
@n 
@nIt's also possible to explicitly specify an RGB value, by including the four 
@ncharacter colour sequence (as used by ColourRGB) within square brackets, eg:
@n 
@n    This is a @*[F010]very dark green foreground@*n.
@n              @[F010]very dark green foreground@n
@n
@nBUILDERS:
@n
@nFinally, this function also allows you to embed MXP tags.  The easiest and 
@nsafest way to do this is via the ( and ) bracket options:
@n    
@n    From here, you can walk @*(north@*).
@n
@nHowever it's also possible to include more explicit MSP tags, like this:
@n 
@n    The baker offers to sell you a @*<send href="buy pie">pie@*</send>.
@n                                   @<send href="buy pie">pie@</send>
@n 
@nNote that the MXP tags will automatically be removed if the user doesn't 
@nsupport MXP, but it's very important you remember to close the tags.
