D-C DIFFICULTY-CLASS

The difficulty-class represents an arbitrary value, relative to the situation - the
more challenging the situation, the higher the value.  Then either a skill, stat or
ability added to a diceroll is compared to the difficulty-class.  If you beat the
difficulty class, then you overcome the situation.

Example:  Fleeing in combat has a D-C of 15, otherwise the opponent(s) will get a free
attack on you.  And fleeing is compared to your TUMBLE ability.  So assuming you have a
TUMBLE rating of 5:
Tumble (5) + DiceRoll 1d20 (rolled a 7) = 12 vs D-C of 15
therefore you failed and
your opponent will get a free attack on you.

See Also:  FLEE TUMBLE
