STYLISTICS-2 STYLE-2 Building guidelines: Rooms: - Room names should be unique
wherever possible, and be short, creative, and descriptive.  Never "A house".  
Instead, "Inside a bustling, messy home".  Not "A road".  "A muddy, sogging,
neglected highway."  Note that long roads and tunnels, etc, are the excep ion to
the rule about not repeating room names.  Always ask yourself "Is this creative
enough?"  Often it is, but sometimes you can do better.  "A hot, dry, desert
highway" works, but it could have been "A sun-baked, elevated road above the
sand" or somethi - Never use "you" in an rdesc.  "You feel a cool breeze."  No, I
don't.  I'm undead and wearing full plate.  Instead, "A cool breeze blows across
the road, bringing with it the scent of melting snow."  You are allowed, however,
to share what someone's impress ons might be, if it helps establish setting.  
Example: "This room in the inn looks far more worn and neglected than the
others.  Rat-eaten bedding indicates that whoever sleeps here isn't very well
respected.  A pair of useless, worn-through boots have been - NEVER describe
actions taken by the player in an rdesc.  "You wince at the sight of" "You step
on a rat" "You kick the skull in frustation" etc.  All bad.  Don't do this.  
The player decides what the player does, NOT THE BUILDER.  - Rdescs should
include all 5 senses wherever reasonable.  Remember, the purpose of an rdesc
isn't to hide a clue in a wall of text.  It's to build setting.  Your players
know nothing about your world except what you tell them.  - Use adjectives.  Be
descriptive.  It's not a chair, it's a short-legged metal chair.  It's not a
tree, it's a mighty, swaying cottonwood.  Tell me about the damn thing, if it's
so interesting you feel you should mention it.  On a related note, if it's in th
room, mention it to build setting - Every noun in the rdesc should have an extra
description.  There are exceptions, but that's the rule.  If you introduce a new
noun in an extra desc, give that a new extra desc.  Let people feel like they
can explore every room in a more immersive way than wandering in and scanning
for mobs and items.  Let people "look book" "look chair" "look statue" etc.  -
Every exit needs a description, especially if it goes nowhere.  If I look down,
what do I see?  What's the floor made of?  Is there anything interesting about
it?  Even if it's completely plain, you can say something about it that builds
setting.  Example, ooking down: "Scuff marks mar the wooden floor around the
legs of the chair, indicating its frequent use" or, looking at up, "Signs of
water damage along the tops of the walls indicate the roof has gone without
repair for too long."  Mobs: - Remember that every mob you place has to have a
reason for being there.  Mobs are part of the setting.  The mobs and the way
they're described are incredibly important in establishing setting, especially
for people who don't look at rooms.  - When designing a mob, ask yourself lots
of questions like this: What is he doing here?  How does he interact with the
environment?  How does he feel about that interaction?  What is he wearing, and
what does that tell me about him AND about the setting?  B d mdesc: "A hairy
gnoll glares at you."  Better mdesc: "A gnoll with long, braided hair and dark tan
fur peers around the area, watching for interlopers.  His armor is a patchwork
of metal scraps, and seems almost to have been assembled with the intention
Items: -If an item is mentioned in an rdesc or mdesc, it should either be an
extra description, or an item that loads in the zone.  -Show setting in your
odesc.  Use it to describe not only the physical object in an informative way,
but also to talk about its place in the world, where applicable.  Example: "This
short, flat, knife is silver embossed with gold.  It usual place is on the utter
tray of Cadaverian bourgeoisie at teatime."  

